  "signature": "ed25519:9b2e4f1a7c3d08e5b6f2a4c1d9e7b3f08a2c5e1d4b7f9a3c6e2d08b1f4a7c3e",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA level 2 requires documented version control, build reproducibility records, and a traceable issue log. The FEA ensemble (Ansys 2021 R2, in-house FDA solver, DePuy Synthes proprietary code) each provided version-pinned release notes, regression test suites with pass/fail logs, and change-control documentation reviewed by the credibility team.",
      "rationale": "All three solver environments demonstrated version-controlled releases with documented regression testing. Ansys 2021 R2 provided NIST-traceable benchmark results. The FDA in-house solver maintains a formal issue-tracking system. DePuy Synthes provided a signed SQA report. Achieved level 3 exceeds the required level 2 for a Medium model-risk context."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification at level 2 requires demonstration that the solver correctly implements the governing equations via at least one benchmark problem with a known analytical or manufactured solution. Each solver must document convergence behavior.",
      "rationale": "Each solver in the ensemble was verified against ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems for linear elastic solid mechanics. Convergence of the iterative solvers was confirmed to residual tolerance 1e-8. Patch test results for the hexahedral and tetrahedral element libraries were documented in the respective verification reports."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires a mesh convergence study demonstrating that the QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) change by less than 5% between the production mesh and a globally refined mesh with element edge lengths halved.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed. The production mesh (mean element edge length 0.8 mm in the screw shank) yielded QoI values within 2.3% of the finest mesh. Richardson extrapolation confirmed the observed convergence rate was consistent with second-order spatial accuracy. Discretization error is therefore bounded and within the level 2 criterion."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 1 requires that solver residuals are monitored and that the solution is confirmed to have converged within the solver's default tolerances.",
      "rationale": "All three solvers reported converged solutions with force residuals below 1e-6 N and displacement residuals below 1e-8 mm. No non-convergence warnings were observed across the 11 specimen simulations. Achieved level 2 because iterative error was additionally bounded by comparison of direct and iterative solver results on a representative sub-model."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires documented model setup procedures, an independent review of the simulation inputs by a second analyst, and a checklist confirming boundary conditions match the ASTM F1717 test fixture geometry.",
      "rationale": "Model setup was performed by one analyst and independently reviewed by a second analyst using a structured checklist. Boundary conditions (fixed inferior block, displacement-controlled superior block, frictionless fixture contacts) were confirmed to replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture. No discrepancies were identified during the independent review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires justification that the chosen constitutive model (linear elastic, isotropic titanium alloy) is appropriate for the loading regime and that any simplifying assumptions are explicitly documented and supported by literature or sensitivity analyses.",
      "rationale": "The Ti-6Al-4V alloy screw is modeled as linear elastic isotropic (E=114 GPa, nu=0.34) consistent with ASTM F136 material certification data. The UHMWPE block is modeled as linear elastic (E=0.89 GPa, nu=0.46) calibrated from coupon tests. Geometric nonlinearity (large displacement) is activated. Sensitivity analyses confirmed that plasticity onset in the screw shank occurs at loads exceeding the 40 mm displacement endpoint, justifying the elastic assumption for the primary QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires that all material properties and geometric inputs are traceable to specimen-specific measurements or certified material data sheets, and that a parameter uncertainty analysis quantifies the sensitivity of QoIs to input variability.",
      "rationale": "Screw geometry was derived from CMM measurements of production screws (mean ± 1 SD reported). Material properties were taken from ASTM F136 certificates of conformance for each lot. A one-at-a-time sensitivity study showed that QoI sensitivity to ±5% variation in elastic modulus was less than 2%, confirming that input uncertainty does not dominate the model error budget."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires that test specimens are drawn from production-representative lots and that dimensional measurements are recorded for each specimen to confirm conformance to nominal geometry.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production-representative lots. Each screw was dimensionally inspected post-assembly; all specimens were within ±0.05 mm of nominal. UHMWPE block density was measured for each block. Achieved level 3 because specimen-specific CMM data were used to individualize the corresponding FEA model geometry for each of the 11 specimens."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single set of ASTM F1717 conditions (6° offset angle, 10 mm/min crosshead displacement rate, ambient temperature). Only one loading configuration was explored; no variation in offset angle or displacement rate was included. The achieved level 1 reflects this limitation — the test conditions replicate the standard protocol but do not span the range of physiological loading scenarios. The credibility team accepted this shortfall given that ASTM F1717 is the regulatory reference standard and the COU is explicitly scoped to that protocol. A risk-benefit evaluation determined that the single-condition coverage is sufficient for the regulatory submission context."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires documented traceability between each experimental input parameter (geometry, material lot, fixture configuration) and the corresponding simulation input, with any unmeasured parameters identified and their assumed values justified.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared mapping 14 experimental inputs to their simulation counterparts. Fixture compliance was measured on the test machine and incorporated as a spring element in the FEA. Contact friction coefficients for the screw-block interface were estimated from literature (mu=0.15 ± 0.05) and a sensitivity study confirmed QoI impact less than 1.5%. All equivalency decisions are documented in the simulation plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires a quantitative comparison metric that accounts for both model error and experimental uncertainty, such as the validation metric E/uval, and that the metric is computed for each QoI and each specimen.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval (model error normalized by combined experimental and model uncertainty) was computed for each of the three QoIs across all 11 specimens. All 33 metric values were below 1.96, satisfying the pre-specified acceptance bound. Additionally, the percentage difference between FEA and experimental mean QoI values was below 10% for all three QoIs across both laboratories."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires a documented justification that the selected QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are mechanistically linked to the clinical failure modes of interest and are measurable with sufficient precision in both the simulation and the experiment.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness characterizes the load-sharing behavior relevant to adjacent-level effects. Yield force is the primary structural integrity metric for regulatory submissions. Force at 40 mm displacement captures post-yield behavior relevant to fatigue life estimation. All three QoIs are directly measurable from ASTM F1717 load-displacement curves and are standard outputs of the FEA post-processor."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires that the validation experiments are conducted under conditions that closely replicate the COU scenario, that the same QoIs are assessed in both the validation and COU contexts, and that any remaining gaps between the validation scenario and the COU are explicitly identified and bounded.",
      "rationale": "The validation experiments directly replicate the COU: same screw design, same ASTM F1717 protocol, same QoIs, same FEA modeling framework. The only gap is that validation used production-representative specimens rather than patient-implanted devices, which is appropriate given the pre-clinical regulatory context. This gap is bounded by the dimensional conformance data and material certification records."
    }
  ],
